		<header>
			
			<h1>Regional cereals surplus but continued challenges</h1>

			
			<h4>
												26 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports on a recent SADC media briefing, during the last rainy season SADC member states ‘have recorded a high general surplus and one of the largest maize surpluses in a decade’. Overall SADC cereals production estimates indicate a 12% increase over last season, but ‘32% higher than the five-year average’. Almost all SADC countries increased their cereals production with ‘exceptionally high increases in production compared to last year … in Botswana (158%), Lesotho (59%), Namibia (40%), Tanzania (35%) and Zambia (41%)’. Production and consumption of non-cereals such as cassava and plantain have also increased (+84%). Taking into account reserves in silos in the region, the SADC region has ‘an estimated surplus of 2.05 million tonnes’. This compares to a deficit of 0.38 million tonnes in 2009. Maize, the region’s staple food, ‘has recorded increased surpluses for the past four years’, with a ‘regional maize surplus of 5.83 million tonnes’ expected for the 2010/11 marketing year.</p><p>However challenges remain at national level, with many countries still having deficits. Overall deficits and import requirements exist in wheat (2.75 million tonnes), rice (0.66 million tonnes) and sorghum/millet (0.37 million tonnes), with the number of people requiring humanitarian assistance increasing to 4.04 million people in eight countries (Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Namibia, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe), up from 3.26 million last year. Thus at the household level ‘the situation is even more challenging in terms of food access.’</p><p>Despite the surplus, the region maintains a ‘high dependence on rain-fed agriculture’, while input use is ‘very low’ (less than half the world average) and the region remains ‘characterised by food shortages, underproduction and declining yields in agriculture, as well as land degradation, unsustainable use of natural resources and environmental degradation’.</p><p>Press reports indicate that rising global wheat prices are likely to lead to increased bread prices in a number of SADC countries, given the high level of import dependency (e.g. 50% in South Africa and 85% in Namibia).</p><p>SADC’s July 2010 food security update shows a highly diverse production performance for basic staples, and highlights the significance of intra-regional trade issues. Currently a more pragmatic approach to intra-regional trade is emerging. One example of this is COMESA’s recent simplified trade regime initiative, with the launch in July 2010 of a simplified trade regime (STR) between Zimbabwe and Zambia, designed to allow small informal traders ‘to enjoy the same duty-free privileges that the FTA has provided to regular traders’. This follows the launch of a similar simplified trade regime between Zambia and Malawi at the end of April 2010.</p><p>Meanwhile, at the SADC level the focus is shifting to the more rigorous application of existing SADC FTA commitments, while at the same time exploring the practical steps which need to be taken towards the <i>de facto</i> establishment of a grand FTA encompassing SACU, SADC and COMESA.</p>
		
		
