				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>With an improved regional situation for cereals supply, issues of intra-regional agricultural trade take centre stage. The reality is that while there is a grain surplus at the regional level, most SADC countries are net food importers. National efforts therefore tend to focus on the design and implementation of national strategies for expanding national food production, strategies which commonly include the use of traditional trade policy tools. In some instances this includes careful assessment of the commercial and ecological sustainability of the policies adopted, with the use of trade policy tools being seen as an essential last resort to be implemented in ways that are least distorting to trade. In other countries a less nuanced approach is adopted.</p><p>This accounts for why, despite general policy commitments to trade liberalisation at both the SADC and COMESA levels, progress in resolving outstanding issues related to trade in cereals and cereal products remains slow in the SADC FTA context. Underpinning these delays is the absence of a clear consensus on the basic framework for national agricultural policies in the SADC region and on the nature of the trade policy tools that can legitimately be used at national level to support specific sectoral development programmes.</p><p>There is no clear consensus on the acceptance of free trade in basic agricultural commodities, as different countries wish to maintain managed trade arrangements in order to protect and nurture specific sectors that are deemed to be of national economic significance, that are central to food safety, or are important for employment creation and the promotion of value-added processing activities. Against this background, the step-by-step approach to agricultural trade liberalisation (e.g. via such initiatives as the COMESA simplified trade regime) may prove most effective on the ground, particularly if this promotes greater transparency and accountability in the implementation of trade policy measures.</p><p>This incremental approach may eventually prove effective in reconciling national agricultural development concerns with regional trade aspirations, in this most politically sensitive of areas – trade in basic foodstuffs.</p>
		</div>
		
